# Create New Page Rule

This rule defines the standard structure and patterns for creating new pages in the application, based on the edit-profile feature architecture.

**⚠️ IMPORTANT: By default, use hard-coded English strings in all examples and implementations. Translations should only be added when explicitly requested by the user.**

See [code-comments.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/_common/code-comments.mdc) for code commenting standards.

**⚠️ MANDATORY:** See [context7-docs.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/_common/context7-docs.mdc) for Context7 MCP requirements and [nextjs-devtools.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/_common/nextjs-devtools.mdc) for Next.js DevTools MCP requirements.

### Why Next.js DevTools MCP Is Mandatory:

- **Prevents Duplicate Routes**: Identifies existing routes before creating new ones
- **Catches Errors Early**: Detects compilation and runtime errors immediately
- **Validates Architecture**: Ensures new pages follow Next.js App Router conventions
- **Runtime Verification**: Confirms pages work correctly in the actual Next.js runtime
- **Better Context**: Provides real-time information about the running application

### Example Workflow:

```typescript
// 1. Initialize (once per session)
nextjs_init({ project_path: '/path/to/project' })

// 2. Discover dev server
nextjs_index() // Returns server info and available tools

// 3. Check current state before creating page
nextjs_call({
  port: '3000',
  toolName: 'get_routes'
})

// 4. After implementation, verify
nextjs_call({
  port: '3000',
  toolName: 'get_errors'
})
```

**Failure to use Next.js DevTools MCP may result in:**

- Duplicate route creation
- Missing error detection
- Architecture violations
- Runtime issues going unnoticed

## ⚠️ CRITICAL: Page Component Requirements

### ALL Pages MUST Be Server Components

**MANDATORY REQUIREMENTS:**

1. **ALL pages MUST be async Server Components** - No page file should have `'use client'` directive
2. **ALL async pages MUST export `generateMetadata`** - Every page component must include metadata generation
3. **If a page needs interactivity**, extract the interactive logic to a separate Client Component and import it in the Server Component page

**Pattern for Pages Requiring Interactivity:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Server Component page with separate Client Component
// app/(feature)/page.tsx
import { Metadata } from 'next'

import { InteractiveComponent } from './_feature/interactive-component'

export default async function FeaturePage() {
  return <InteractiveComponent />
}

export async function generateMetadata(): Promise<Metadata> {
  return {
    description: 'Page description',
    title: 'Page Title'
  }
}
```

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Client Component for interactivity
// app/(feature)/_feature/interactive-component.tsx
'use client'

import { useState } from 'react'

export function InteractiveComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState()
  // ... interactive logic
  return <div>...</div>
}
```

**❌ WRONG: Client Component Page**

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Page as Client Component
'use client'

export default function FeaturePage() {
  // This violates the requirement
}
```

**❌ WRONG: Missing generateMetadata**

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Async page without generateMetadata
export default async function FeaturePage() {
  return <div>...</div>
  // Missing generateMetadata export
}
```

**❌ WRONG: Non-async Page**

```tsx
// ❌ WRONG: Non-async page
export default function FeaturePage() {
  return <div>...</div>
  // Should be: export default async function FeaturePage()
}
```

### generateMetadata Pattern

**For Static Pages:**

```tsx
export async function generateMetadata(): Promise<Metadata> {
  return {
    description: 'Page description',
    title: 'Page Title'
  }
}
```

**For Dynamic Pages (with params):**

```tsx
type PageProps = {
  params: Promise<{ id: string }>
}

export async function generateMetadata({
  params
}: PageProps): Promise<Metadata> {
  const { id } = await params

  // Optionally fetch data for metadata
  const data = await fetchData(id)

  return {
    description: data?.description || 'Default description',
    title: data?.name || 'Default Title'
  }
}
```

## Page Structure Requirements

### 1. Page Header Component

Every page MUST include a `PageHeader` component with:

- `title`: Main page title
- `description`: Brief description of the page purpose
- `children`: Optional content (typically submit buttons for forms)
- `resourceName`: (Optional) For edit pages, the actual resource name to display in breadcrumb

```tsx
import { PageHeader } from '@/components/custom/page-header'
;<PageHeader title="Page Title" description="Page description">
  {/* Optional children content */}
</PageHeader>
```

#### PageHeader resourceName Prop for Edit and Show Pages

**When viewing or editing a specific resource, use the `resourceName` prop to display the actual resource name in the breadcrumb trail.**

The `resourceName` prop is used by the `SmartBreadcrumb` component to:
- Replace generic breadcrumb segments with the actual resource name
- Provide better context for users navigating through the app
- Create more meaningful breadcrumb trails like "Spaces > Layouts > Conference Room Layout" instead of "Spaces > Layouts > Edit"
- Apply to both edit pages (`/edit`) and show/detail pages (`/[id]`)

**Example: Edit Page with Resource Name**

```tsx
'use client'

import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { PageHeader } from '@/components/custom/page-header'

export function EditResourceForm({ resourceId }: { resourceId: string }) {
  const { data: resource } = useQuery(getResourceByIdQuery(resourceId))

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-5">
      <PageHeader
        description="Update resource information"
        resourceName={resource?.name} // Displays actual resource name in breadcrumb
        title="Edit Resource"
      >
        <form.AppForm>
          <form.SubmitButton form="edit-form">
            Save Changes
          </form.SubmitButton>
        </form.AppForm>
      </PageHeader>
      {/* Form content */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

**Example: Show/Detail Page with Resource Name**

```tsx
'use client'

import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { PageHeader } from '@/components/custom/page-header'
import { Tabs, TabsContent } from '@/components/ui/tabs'

export function ResourceDetailPage({ resourceId }: { resourceId: string }) {
  const { data: resource } = useQuery(getResourceByIdQuery(resourceId))

  return (
    <>
      <PageHeader
        description="Resource details"
        resourceName={resource?.name} // Shows actual resource name in breadcrumb
        title={resource?.name || 'Resource'}
      >
        <HeaderActions
          edit={{ path: `/resources/${resourceId}/edit` }}
          // ... other actions
        />
      </PageHeader>
      <Tabs defaultValue="overview">
        <TabsContent value="overview">
          {/* Resource details */}
        </TabsContent>
      </Tabs>
    </>
  )
}
```

#### Handling Resources with Arabic/English Translations

**When viewing or editing resources that have `ar` and `en` translations, use the `useLocale()` hook to select the appropriate language for the `resourceName`.**

**Pattern for Resources with Translations:**

```tsx
'use client'

import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { useLocale } from '@/hooks/use-locale'
import { PageHeader } from '@/components/custom/page-header'

type ResourceWithTranslations = {
  id: number
  translations?: {
    ar: { name: string }
    en: { name: string }
  }
}

export function EditResourceForm({ resourceId }: { resourceId: string }) {
  const { isRTL } = useLocale()

  const { data: resource } = useQuery<ResourceWithTranslations>(
    getResourceByIdQuery(resourceId)
  )

  // Select translation based on current locale
  const resourceName = isRTL
    ? resource?.translations?.ar.name
    : resource?.translations?.en.name

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-5">
      <PageHeader
        description="Update resource information"
        resourceName={resourceName} // Locale-aware resource name
        title="Edit Resource"
      >
        <form.AppForm>
          <form.SubmitButton form="edit-form">
            Save Changes
          </form.SubmitButton>
        </form.AppForm>
      </PageHeader>
      {/* Form content */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

**Real Example: Space Layout Form**

```tsx
'use client'

import { useQuery } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { useLocale } from '@/hooks/use-locale'
import { getMasterSpaceLayoutByIdQuery } from '@/query/master-space-layouts'

export function SpaceLayoutForm({ layoutId }: { layoutId: string }) {
  const { isRTL } = useLocale()

  const { data: layout } = useQuery(getMasterSpaceLayoutByIdQuery(layoutId))

  // Get localized layout name
  const layoutName = isRTL
    ? layout?.translations?.ar.name
    : layout?.translations?.en.name

  return (
    <div className="flex flex-col gap-5">
      <PageHeader
        description="Update space layout info"
        resourceName={layoutName} // Shows "Conference Room" instead of "Edit"
        title="Edit Space Layout"
      >
        <form.AppForm>
          <form.SubmitButton form="edit-space-layout-form">
            Save Changes
          </form.SubmitButton>
        </form.AppForm>
      </PageHeader>
      {/* Form fields */}
    </div>
  )
}
```

**Key Requirements for Translated Resources:**

- ✅ Import and use `useLocale()` hook from `@/hooks/use-locale`
- ✅ Check `isRTL` to determine current language direction
- ✅ Use ternary operator to select appropriate translation: `isRTL ? ar : en`
- ✅ Handle optional chaining for translations: `resource?.translations?.ar.name`
- ✅ Pass the localized name to PageHeader's `resourceName` prop
- ✅ This pattern applies to all resources with bilingual support (spaces, layouts, amenities, types, categories, etc.)

### 2. Form Integration with PageHeader

When a page contains a form, the submit button MUST be placed as children of the PageHeader:

```tsx
<PageHeader title="Form Page" description="Form description">
  <form.AppForm>
    <form.SubmitButton form="unique-form-id">
      Submit Button Text
    </form.SubmitButton>
  </form.AppForm>
</PageHeader>
```

- **Navigation-first workflow**: When adding CRUD flows for data tables, default to dedicated `/create` and `/[id]/edit` pages that render the form. Only use inline dialogs when the product requirements explicitly demand them.

### 3. Form Structure Requirements

- **Unique Form ID**: Every form MUST have a unique `id` attribute
- **Form Prop**: The `form.SubmitButton` MUST have a `form` prop matching the form's `id`
- **Form Container**: The form element MUST have the same `id` as the submit button's `form` prop

```tsx
<form
  onSubmit={(e) => {
    e.preventDefault()
    form.handleSubmit()
  }}
  id="unique-form-id" // Must match form prop in SubmitButton
  className="w-full flex-1 space-y-5 px-5"
>
  {/* Form content */}
</form>
```

### 4. Content Layout Structure

Content beneath the header MUST follow this structure:

#### For Pages with Forms:

**⚠️ CRITICAL: Form pages MUST follow this pattern:**

**When a form component is used directly in a page (not inside tabs), it MUST receive `className="m-5"` from the page component:**

- **✅ DO**: Pass `className="m-5"` when form is direct child of `PageHeader` (no tabs)
- **❌ DON'T**: Pass `className="m-5"` when form is inside `TabsContent` (tabs handle spacing)

```tsx
import { Metadata } from 'next'

import { {Resource}Form } from '@/app/(app)/{feature}/_{feature}/forms/{resource}-form'

export default async function Create{Resource}Page() {
  return <{Resource}Form className="m-5" />
}

export async function generateMetadata(): Promise<Metadata> {
  return {
    description: 'Create a new {resource}',
    title: 'Create {Resource}'
  }
}
```

**Form Component Structure:**

Form components should accept `className?: string` prop and merge it using `cn()` utility:

```tsx
type {Resource}FormProps = {
  className?: string
  isEdit?: boolean
  // ... other props
}

export const {Resource}Form: React.FC<{Resource}FormProps> = ({
  className,
  // ... other props
}) => {
  // ... form logic ...

  return (
    <div className={cn('flex flex-col gap-5', className)}>
      <PageHeader title="..." description="...">
        <form.AppForm>
          <form.SubmitButton form="unique-form-id">Submit</form.SubmitButton>
        </form.AppForm>
      </PageHeader>
      <form
        id="unique-form-id"
        className="w-full flex-1 space-y-5 px-5"
        onSubmit={(e) => {
          e.preventDefault()
          form.handleSubmit()
        }}
      >
        <FormFields form={form} id="section-1" title="Section 1" />
        <FormFields form={form} id="section-2" title="Section 2" />
      </form>
    </div>
  )
}
```

**Pattern for Forms Inside Tabs:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Form inside tabs - NO m-5 needed (tabs handle spacing)
<TabsContent value="form">
  <{Resource}Form /> {/* No className prop - tabs handle spacing */}
</TabsContent>
```

#### For Pages without Forms (Table Pages):

**⚠️ CRITICAL: Table pages MUST follow this pattern:**

**When a table component is used directly in a page (not inside tabs), it MUST receive `className="m-5"` from the page component:**

- **✅ DO**: Pass `className="m-5"` when table is direct child of `PageHeader` (no tabs)
- **❌ DON'T**: Pass `className="m-5"` when table is inside `TabsContent` (tabs handle spacing)

```tsx
import { Metadata } from 'next'

import { {Resource}Table } from '@/app/(app)/{feature}/_{feature}/tables/{resource}-table'
import {PageHeader} from '@/components/custom/page-header'

export default async function {Resource}TablePage() {
  return (
    <>
      <PageHeader description="Manage and view {Resources}" title="{Resources}" />
      <{Resource}Table className="m-5" />
    </>
  )
}

export async function generateMetadata(): Promise<Metadata> {
  return {
    description: 'Manage and view {Resources}',
    title: '{Resources}'
  }
}
```

**Pattern for Tables Inside Tabs:**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT: Table inside tabs - NO m-5 needed (tabs handle spacing)
<TabsContent value="table">
  <{Resource}Table /> {/* No className prop - tabs handle spacing */}
</TabsContent>
```

**Client Component Pattern (Table Component):**

The table component MUST accept `className` prop and use `cn()` to merge it. The `toolbar` prop MUST be passed to `DataTable`, and `main` must use `className={cn('relative', className)}`:

```tsx
'use client'

import { cn } from '@/utils'
import { DataTable, DataTableToolbar } from '@/components/data-table'

export const {Resource}Table: React.FC<{ className?: string }> = ({
  className
}) => {
  // ... table logic ...

  return (
    <main className={cn('relative', className)}>
      <DataTable
        toolbar={
          <DataTableToolbar
            createButtonHref="/{feature}/create"
            table={table}
          />
        }
        table={table}
      />
    </main>
  )
}
```

**Key Requirements:**

- ✅ Page is **server component** (async function, no `'use client'`)
- ✅ Page includes `PageHeader` with `title` and `description`
- ✅ Client component accepts `className` prop
- ✅ Pass `className="m-5"` from page to client component
- ✅ Client component uses `cn()` to merge `className` with base classes
- ✅ Client component's main element uses merged `className`

### 5. Feature Folder Structure and Form Declaration

Every page MUST have a corresponding folder with the same name but starting with an underscore (`_feature_name/`). This folder contains all components, hooks, and config files related to the feature.

#### Folder Structure Requirements:

- **Naming Convention**: Folder name should match the page folder name with an underscore prefix
- **Contents**: All feature-specific components, hooks, utilities, and configuration files
- **Organization**: Keep related functionality grouped within this folder

#### Form Declaration Requirements:

Every form in the application MUST declare a `form-options.tsx` file that contains:

1. **formOptions** with `defaultValues` typed as `FeatureSchema`
2. **featureSchema** as a Zod v4 object for validation
3. **FeatureSchema** type inferred from the schema

```tsx
// _feature_name/form-options.tsx
import { formOptions } from '@tanstack/react-form'
import { z } from 'zod/v4'

export const featureForm = formOptions({
  defaultValues: {
    // form default values
  } as FeatureSchema
})

export const featureSchema = z.object({
  // validation schema
})

export type FeatureSchema = z.infer<typeof featureSchema>
```

#### Feature Component Structure:

```tsx
// _feature_name/section-fields.tsx
import { featureForm } from '@/app/(app)/path/_feature_name/form-options'
import { withForm } from '@/components/form'

export const SectionFields = withForm({
  ...featureForm,
  render: function Render({ form }) {
    return (
      <div className="space-y-5">
        <form.AppField
          name="field_name"
          children={(field) => <field.Input label="Field Label" />}
        />
        {/* Additional fields */}
      </div>
    )
  }
})
```

#### Example Folder Structure:

```
app/(app)/settings/edit-profile/
├── page.tsx
└── _edit_profile/
    ├── form-options.tsx
    ├── basic-info.tsx
    ├── password.tsx
    └── other-components.tsx
```

### 6. Vertical Stepper Integration

When using forms with multiple sections:

- Each section MUST have a unique `id` that matches the stepper step `id`
- Use `Card` components for each section with matching `id`
- Stepper steps MUST correspond to form sections

### 7. Spacing Requirements

- All form fields MUST have `space-y-5`

### 8. RTL-Friendly Classes Requirement

**CRITICAL: All spacing, positioning, and alignment classes MUST use RTL-friendly logical properties.**

```tsx
// ✅ CORRECT - RTL-friendly classes
<div className="ms-4 me-2 ps-4 pe-2">  // Logical margin/padding
<div className="start-0 end-0">        // Logical positioning
<div className="text-start">           // Logical text alignment
<div className="border-s-2 border-e-4"> // Logical borders

// ❌ WRONG - RTL-unfriendly classes
<div className="ml-4 mr-2 pl-4 pr-2">  // Physical margin/padding
<div className="left-0 right-0">     // Physical positioning
<div className="text-left">           // Physical text alignment
<div className="border-l-2 border-r-4"> // Physical borders
```

**See [styling-guide.mdc](mdc:.cursor/rules/styling/styling-guide.mdc) for complete RTL migration guide and RTL-friendly class reference.**

### 9. Detail Pages with PageHeader and HeaderActions

**⚠️ CRITICAL: When using PageHeader with HeaderActions in server components, you MUST move PageHeader into a client component.**

**❌ WRONG: Passing functions from server to client component**

```tsx
// ❌ DON'T: Server component passing mutationOptions (functions) to client component
export default async function DetailPage({ params }) {
  const workspace = await fetchWorkspace(id)
  const toggleMutation = mutationOptions({ ... }) // Contains functions

  return (
    <PageHeader title={workspace.name}>
      <HeaderActions
        activeToggleMutation={{
          mutationOptions: toggleMutation // ❌ Can't pass functions from server to client
        }}
      />
    </PageHeader>
  )
}
```

**✅ CORRECT: Move PageHeader and HeaderActions to client component**

```tsx
// ✅ DO: Server component uses prefetchQuery with HydrationBoundary
import { dehydrate, HydrationBoundary } from '@tanstack/react-query'

export default async function DetailPage({ params }) {
  const { id } = await params
  const queryClient = getQueryClient()

  try {
    await queryClient.prefetchQuery(getWorkspaceByIdQuery(id))
  } catch (error) {
    console.error(error)
  }

  return (
    <HydrationBoundary state={dehydrate(queryClient)}>
      <WorkspaceTabs workspaceId={id} />
    </HydrationBoundary>
  )
}
```

```tsx
// ✅ DO: Client component uses useQuery to read prefetched data and creates mutationOptions
'use client'

import { useQuery, mutationOptions } from '@tanstack/react-query'
import { HeaderActions } from '@/components/custom/header-actions'
import { PageHeader } from '@/components/custom/page-header'

export const WorkspaceTabs: React.FC<{
  workspaceId: number | string
}> = ({ workspaceId }) => {
  // ✅ CORRECT: useQuery reads prefetched data from HydrationBoundary
  const { data: workspace, isLoading, isError } = useQuery(getWorkspaceByIdQuery(workspaceId))

  if (isLoading) return null
  if (!workspace || isError) return <NotFound title="Workspace not found" />

  // Create mutationOptions in client component (can contain functions)
  const toggleMutation = mutationOptions({
    meta: { invalidatesQuery: [['workspaces']] },
    mutationFn: async () => { ... }
  })

  return (
    <>
      <PageHeader
        description="Meeting Room"
        image={workspace.photo || undefined}
        isAvatar
        title={workspace.name}
      >
        <HeaderActions
          activeToggleMutation={{
            initialStatus: workspace.status,
            mutationFnParam: workspaceId,
            mutationOptions: toggleMutation, // ✅ Functions created in client component
            permissionKey: PERMISSIONS.WORKSPACES_UPDATE
          }}
          edit={{
            path: `/workspaces/${workspaceId}/edit`,
            permissionKey: PERMISSIONS.WORKSPACES_UPDATE
          }}
        />
      </PageHeader>
      <Tabs defaultValue="pricing" useUrlState>
        {/* Tabs content */}
      </Tabs>
    </>
  )
}
```

**Key Requirements:**

- ✅ **Server component**: Only fetches data and passes serializable props (strings, numbers, objects without functions)
- ✅ **Client component**: Creates `mutationOptions` and renders `PageHeader` with `HeaderActions`
- ✅ **No function props**: Never pass functions (including `mutationOptions`) from server to client components
- ✅ **Data props only**: Pass only data objects (name, photo, status, etc.) from server to client
